uzian body is not necessarily a human body, but the lines of enquiry here all illuminate the idea of the human body and thinking about formation, origins and becoming in relation to power, creativity and affect. Key features Brings a new perspective to Spinozan and Nietzschean ideas of the body Contributors include Ella Brians, Claire Colebrook, Rebecca Coleman, Anna Cutler, Patricia MacCormack, Iain MacKenzie, John Protevi, Peta Malins, Philipa Rothfield and Nathan Widder Of interest to those concerned with theories of the body and affectivity, and those interested in performance arts, film and contemporary culture  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aDeleuze, Gilles, -- 1925-1995. 0aMind and body. 4aPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Mind & Body.2bisacsh1 aBrians, Ella, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColebrook, Claire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColeman, Rebecca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCutler, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHughes, Joe, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aHughes, Joe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacCormack, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacKenzie, Iain, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMalins, Peta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aProtevi, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRothfield, Philipa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWidder, Nathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist 